# Handyman Template Project Rules

## Project Overview

This is a handyman service website template built with Astro, TypeScript, and Tailwind CSS.

## Technology Stack

- **Framework**: Astro
- **Language**: TypeScript
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS
- **Package Manager**: pnpm (not npm)
- **Editor**: Cursor (not VS Code)

## Code Style Guidelines

### General Principles

- Follow DRY principle (Don't Repeat Yourself)
- Write clean, readable, and maintainable code
- Use early returns for better readability
- Prefer descriptive variable and function names
- Use const instead of functions where possible
- Use Types instead of interfaces
- Use named functions instead of arrow functions

### Component Props Pattern

- Always use Types (not interfaces) for component props
- Define props with optional properties and default values
- Use destructuring with default values in the frontmatter
- Example pattern:

```typescript
export type Props = {
  title?: string
  description?: string
  buttonText?: string
  buttonHref?: string
  backgroundClass?: string
}

const {
  title = 'Default Title',
  description = 'Default description',
  buttonText = 'Default Button',
  buttonHref = '#',
  backgroundClass = 'default-bg-class',
} = Astro.props
```

### Event Handling

- Event functions should be named with "handle" prefix
- Example: `handleClick` for onClick, `handleKeyDown` for onKeyDown

### Accessibility

- Implement accessibility features on interactive elements
- Include tabindex="0", aria-label, on:click, and on:keydown attributes
- Ensure proper semantic HTML structure

### Styling Guidelines

- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes
- Prefer Tailwind color utility class names over hex codes
- Use "class:" instead of ternary operators in class tags when possible
- Minimum font size should be text-base, prefer text-lg for better readability
- Avoid xs or small font sizes unless specifically requested

### Import Paths

- Use '@...' import paths instead of relative '../../...' paths
- Use the configured path aliases from tsconfig.json
- Examples:
  - `import { Button } from '@components/ui/Button'`
  - `import Layout from '@layouts/Layout.astro'`
  - `import { siteConfig } from '@config'`
  - `import '@styles/global.css'`

### Configuration Usage

- **ALWAYS use centralized configuration** from `@config/` instead of hardcoded values
- Import and use configuration objects for all site data:
  - `siteConfig` - Site metadata, branding, copyright
  - `socialConfig` - Social media platforms and links
  - `contactConfig` - Contact information and business hours
  - `navigationConfig` - Navigation menus and links
- Use the combined `config` object for convenience:
  ```typescript
  import { config } from '@config'
  const siteName = config.site.name
  const socialLinks = config.social.platforms
  ```
- Use configuration utilities for link handling:
  ```typescript
  import { createLink, getLinkAttributes } from '@config'
  ```
- **Never hardcode** site names, contact info, social links, or navigation items

### Comments

- Minimize comments - only comment complex functions
- Do not comment HTML and CSS
- Avoid generic or redundant information

### Animations

- Use GSAP for animations when needed
- Avoid random shortcuts - study the theme carefully before making changes

### File Structure

- Components go in `src/components/`
- UI components go in `src/components/ui/`
- Styles go in `src/styles/`
- Configuration goes in `src/config/`
- Utilities go in `src/lib/`

### Astro Component Structure

- Always use the standard Astro component pattern with frontmatter
- Define Props type in the frontmatter section
- Use destructuring with default values for all props
- Follow this exact structure:

```astro
---
export type Props = {
  // Define all props as optional with proper types
  title?: string
  description?: string
  // ... other props
}

const {
  // Destructure with meaningful defaults
  title = 'Default Title',
  description = 'Default description',
  // ... other destructured props
} = Astro.props
---

<!-- Component HTML/JSX here -->
```

### Build and Commands

- Do not suggest or run build commands automatically
- Provide commands without executing them - user will run manually
- Do not suggest installing packages globally

### Design Consistency

- Do not change the design when implementing features
- Maintain existing design patterns and styling

